@node Doom Emacs
@subsection Doom Emacs

Add the following to your @samp{packages.el}:
@lisp
(package! majutsu :recipe (:host github :repo "0WD0/majutsu"))
@end lisp

@node use-package with straightel
@subsection use-package with straight.el

@lisp
(use-package majutsu
  :straight (:host github :repo "0WD0/majutsu"))
@end lisp

@node use-package @samp{vc} (Emacs 30+)
@subsection use-package @samp{:vc} (Emacs 30+)

The built-in @samp{use-package} @samp{:vc} keyword is available in Emacs 30 and later.
Use @samp{:rev :newest} to follow the repository's current default branch:
@lisp
(use-package majutsu
  :vc (:url "https://github.com/0WD0/majutsu"
       :rev :newest))
@end lisp

@node package-vc (Emacs 29+)
@subsection package-vc (Emacs 29+)

Emacs 29 added built-in @samp{package-vc} support. Install Majutsu directly@comma{} then
configure it with @samp{use-package}:
@lisp
(unless (package-installed-p 'majutsu)
  (package-vc-install
   '(majutsu :url "https://github.com/0WD0/majutsu")))

(use-package majutsu)
@end lisp

@node Manual Installation
@subsection Manual Installation

Clone the repository and add it to your @samp{load-path}:
@lisp
(add-to-list 'load-path "/path/to/majutsu")
(require 'majutsu)
@end lisp

@node Post-Installation Tasks
@section Post-Installation Tasks

@strong{Vanilla:} No keymap setup is required; Majutsu's native bindings are active
as soon as its modes load.

@strong{Evil:} Majutsu detects Evil@comma{} installs its normal-state integration by default@comma{}
and opens Majutsu buffers in the configured Evil state.  Customize this with
@samp{M-x customize-group RET majutsu-evil RET}.

@node Getting Started
@chapter Getting Started

Start from a file or Dired buffer whose @code{default-directory} is inside an
existing Jujutsu repository@comma{} then run @code{M-x majutsu-log} (the shorter
@code{M-x majutsu} is an alias).  With a prefix argument@comma{} or when the current
directory is outside a repository@comma{} Majutsu asks which directory to use.  If
that directory is not a repository either@comma{} it asks before running @samp{jj git
init}; declining leaves the directory unchanged.

The log buffer is the safest place to learn the interface.  Find the working
copy revision@comma{} marked @samp{@@}.

@strong{Vanilla:} Use @code{n} and @code{p} to move by revision section.  @code{TAB} expands or
collapses the section at point@comma{} while @code{[} and @code{]} move to a visible parent or
child.

@strong{Evil:} Majutsu starts the log in Normal state.  Use @code{C-j} and @code{C-k} to move by
section; @code{g j} and @code{g k} move between sibling sections.  @code{TAB} expands or
collapses the section at point@comma{} while @code{[} and @code{]} move to a visible parent or
child.

Point is significant: commands opened from the log use the revision under
point as their default.  In particular@comma{} @code{RET} on a revision runs @samp{jj edit}; it
changes which revision the workspace edits@comma{} so do not use it merely to inspect
a revision.

To inspect without running a history-rewriting command@comma{} put point on @samp{@@} and
press @code{D} (@code{majutsu-diff-dwim}).  The resulting diff buffer shows the current
change.

@strong{Vanilla:} @code{TAB} folds files or hunks@comma{} @code{n} and @code{p} move through sections@comma{} and
@code{q} returns to the log.

@strong{Evil:} @code{TAB} folds files or hunks@comma{} @code{C-j} and @code{C-k} move through sections@comma{} and
@code{q} returns to the log without leaving Normal state.

For an explicit selection@comma{} press @code{d} in the log to open the Diff transient.
Its @samp{-r/r} entry has two paths: @samp{-r} reads a revset@comma{} while @code{r} toggles the
revision at point into the @samp{--revisions} selection.  Press @code{d} to execute the
diff@comma{} or @code{c} to clear the selection first.  This does not invoke a rewrite
command@comma{} although jj may snapshot changed working-copy files before producing
output.  Selections only become arguments when an action is executed.

Use @code{?} to open the dispatcher and see the commands valid in the current
buffer.

@strong{Vanilla:} A safe first loop is: move through the log@comma{} inspect a diff@comma{} return
with @code{q}@comma{} and refresh with @code{g}.  If a jj command fails@comma{} press @code{$} to open the
process buffer and read its complete output.

@strong{Evil:} A safe first loop is: move through the log in Normal state@comma{} inspect a
diff@comma{} return with @code{q}@comma{} and refresh with @code{g r}.  If a jj command fails@comma{} press
@code{`} to open the process buffer and read its complete output.

Only after this loop is familiar should you move on to commands in
@emph{Manipulating}@comma{} which can rewrite repository history and may ask for
confirmation.

